(1)

17-29 Carmine Street, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Bleecker Street. At 17-19 Carmine Street is Bertini's Theatre.
1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)

The same, showing the new Church of Our Lady of Pompeii, built in 1926-1927 on the site of Nos. 17-25, to replace the old church, which stood in the path of the southward extension of Sixth Avenue.
March 15, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)
Bleecker Street, south side, from Carmine to Hancock Streets, the southernmost two blocks of that section of Bleecker Street which was originally Herring Street. The old Church of Our Lady of Pompeii is seen at the S.W. corner of Downing Street.
Beyond the six-story building at the right, notice Nos. 226-220,
frame houses with brick fronts.
Late 1926.

(2)
A view from the roof of 24 Minetta Lane, showing the same part of Bleecker Street during the construction of the city subway and of the Sixth Avenue Extension, which will absorb all of Bleecker Street on the southwest side from numbers 224 to 208.
October 11, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

P. L. Sperr.

Carmine Street, from Bleecker Street to Sixth Avenue showing also Sixth Avenue, east side, from Minetta Lane to 3rd Street. On the east side, 20 to 2 Carmine Street, from Bleecker Street to Minetta Lane, and 4 to 16 Sixth Avenue, from Minetta Lane to 3rd (formerly Amity) Street, are shortly to be demolished for the southward extension of Sixth Avenue.

Late 1926.

27, 29 Carmine Street, adjoining the clearing at the N.W. corner of Bleecker Street, where the new church building of Our Lady of Pompeii is to be erected. The houses seen across the clearing are those on the north side of Leroy Street, adjoining and at the corner of Bleecker Street.

May 26, 1926.

Underwood & Underwood.

27, 29 Carmine Street, adjoining the clearing at the N.W. corner of Bleecker Street, a rear view, showing the rear of both houses and the backyard of No. 27, also Nos. 22 and 26 across the street on the southeast side.

May 26, 1926.

Underwood & Underwood.

235, 239 Bleecker Street, north side, between Carmine and Cornelia Streets. No. 235 is an old frame house, papered and painted in front to resemble brick.

1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

231-233-235 Bleecker Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Carmine Street. No. 231, or 15 Carmine Street, is a frame house with a brick front, and No. 235 is another old frame. This is in that section of Bleecker Street, from Hancock Street (now absorbed by Sixth Avenue) to Christopher Street, which was originally called Herring Street.

March 27, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

27 Carmine Street, north side, west of Bleecker Street. Compare this with the front view taken in May, 1926, by Underwood & Underwood. March 27, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

31, 29, 21, 15-5 Carmine Street, north side, east across Bleecker Street to Sixth Avenue and Minetta Lane. The new church of Our Lady of Pompeii, built in 1926, occupies the site of Nos. 25-17, inclusive. Notice the campanile, or bell tower.
March 27, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
